T1  - Identification of Endogenous Social Effects: The Reflection Problem
PY  - 1993
Y1  - 1993/07/01
DO  - 10.2307/2298123
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 60
IS  - 3
SP  - 531
EP  - 542
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper examines the reflection problem that arises when a researcher observing the distribution of behaviour in a population tries to infer whether the average behaviour in some group influences the behaviour of the individuals that comprise the group. It is found that inference is not possible unless the researcher has prior information specifying the compisition of reference groups. If this information is available, the prospects for inference depend critically on the population relationship between the variables defining reference groups and those directly affecting outcomes. Inference is difficult to implossible if these variables are functionally dependent or are statistically independent. The prospects are better if the variables defining reference groups and those directly affecting outcomes are moderately related in the population.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2298123
ER  - 



